data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` — it's more precise because it scopes the assertion to the exact throwing line, not the entire method:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

You can also capture the exception to assert on its properties:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
```

**Why this is better:** `[ExpectedException]` catches exceptions from *any* line in the method (including Arrange), masking bugs. `Assert.ThrowsExactly` targets only the specific call. It also matches the **exact** type — use `Assert.Throws<T>` instead if you want to match derived exception types too.
